{"id":"2209.14938","submitter":"Stefka Asenova","authors":"Johan Segers and Stefka Asenova","title":"Max-linear graphical models with heavy-tailed factors on trees of\n  transitive tournaments","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ME","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Graphical models with heavy-tailed factors can be used to model extremal\ndependence or causality between extreme events. In a Bayesian network,\nvariables are recursively defined in terms of their parents according to a\ndirected acyclic graph (DAG). We focus on max-linear graphical models with\nrespect to a special type of graphs, which we call a tree of transitive\ntournaments. The latter are block graphs combining in a tree-like structure a\nfinite number of transitive tournaments, each of which is a DAG in which every\ntwo nodes are connected. We study the limit of the joint tails of the\nmax-linear model conditionally on the event that a given variable exceeds a\nhigh threshold. Under a suitable condition, the limiting distribution involves\nthe factorization into independent increments along the shortest trail between\ntwo variables, thereby imitating the behavior of a Markov random field. We are\nalso interested in the identifiability of the model parameters in case some\nvariables are latent and only a subvector is observed. It turns out that the\nparameters are identifiable under a criterion on the nodes carrying the latent\nvariables which is easy and quick to check.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2022 16:55:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2023 15:37:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-06-08"}
