{"id":"2209.15057","submitter":"Hao-Tian Liu","authors":"Hao-Tian Liu, Weipeng Chen, Wen Huang","title":"Surprising impact of random impurities on the anomalous Hall effect in\n  chiral superconductors","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures. Version with considerable expansion. Added new\n  calculations and discussions, corrected an error in the two-band calculation","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The anomalous Hall effect and the closely related polar Kerr effect are among\nthe most direct evidence of chiral Cooper pairing in some superconductors.\nWhile it has been known that disorder or multiband pairing is typically needed\nfor these effects to manifest, there is a lack of direct real-space\ninvestigation with regard to how disorder impacts the Hall response in both\nsingle-band and multiband chiral superconductors. On the basis of the chiral\nsuperconducting models often adopted for Sr$_2$RuO$_4$, we study in this work\nthe anomalous Hall effect in the presence of random impurities on a real-space\nlattice. The single-band chiral p-wave ($p_x+ip_y$) calculation qualitatively\nreproduces the Hall conductivity obtained in previous skew-scattering-type\ndiagramatic analyses, along with some quantitative difference due primarily to\ncontributions involving impurity-induced in-gap states. The Hall response of\nthe non-p-wave chiral states (such as $d_{x^2-y^2}+id_{xy}$), however, depends\nsensitively on the form of the impurity potential as well as on the order\nparameter self-consistency. In particular, while pointlike impurities induce\nonly minuscule Hall response in non-self-consistent calculations,\nself-consistency and finite-range impurity potentials can both lead to\nsubstantial Hall conductivity. On the other hand, the intrinsic Hall\nconductivity in multiband chiral superconductors, which originates from\ninterband transitions, decreases parametrically as disorder suppresses the\nsuperconducting order parameter. In addition, we check that random impurities\ndo not induce anomalous Hall effect in non-chiral but time-reversal symmetry\nbreaking superconducting states the likes of $s+i d_{x^2-y^2}$ and\n$d_{x^2-y^2}+i g_{xy(x^2-y^2)}$. We briefly remark on the implications of our\nresults for Kerr effect measurements.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2022 19:01:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 5 Apr 2023 03:14:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-06"}
